      ],
      "scripts": [
        {
          "number": 1,
          "script": "Welcome to this course on AI in contract review, and specifically what AI tends to get wrong. Now, AI tools have become remarkably capable in recent years, and many organisations are using them to speed up contract review. But here is the thing: fast does not always mean accurate, and in legal work, the gaps really matter. AI can struggle with subtle risks that are buried in the wording of a clause, and it often loses track of the broader context that surrounds a contract. Legal language is full of nuance, and automated tools can easily misread or simply overlook it. What makes this particularly tricky is that the errors are not always obvious. You will not always get a glaring red flag. Some of the most significant mistakes can look perfectly fine on the surface. That is exactly why human review remains so important. Throughout this course, we will explore where these gaps appear and why they matter in practice."
        },
        {
          "number": 2,
          "script": "So let's start by looking at where AI actually struggles in contract review, because understanding these blind spots is really the foundation of everything we'll cover in this course. AI tools are genuinely impressive at scanning large volumes of text quickly, but they tend to work at a surface level. They can spot a word or a clause, but they often miss what that word actually means in context. For example, AI won't pick up on the tone of a negotiation, or recognise that a particular phrase carries a very different weight in, say, the construction industry compared to financial services. It also tends to overlook obligations that aren't written down explicitly but are clearly implied by the surrounding terms. And when language is deliberately vague or ambiguous, which happens quite often in contracts, AI can struggle to flag that as a problem at all. So the short version is: AI reads the words, but it doesn't always understand the meaning behind them."
        },
        {
          "number": 3,
          "script": "So even when AI tools do a solid job of flagging obvious issues, there are whole categories of risk they consistently miss. Take vague language, for example. Words like \"reasonable\" or \"timely\" might look harmless, but they can hide serious disagreements down the line. AI often reads those words at face value. Then there is context. A clause that seems perfectly fair in one business relationship can mean something quite different in another, and AI has no way of knowing your specific situation. Implied duties are another blind spot. Sometimes obligations exist even when they are not written down, based on law or industry practice, and automated tools rarely pick those up. And here is something people often overlook: tone. The way a contract is written can tell you a lot about how the other party intends to behave. AI does not read between the lines the way an experienced human does. That is exactly the skill we are going to build in this lesson."
        },
        {
          "number": 4,
          "script": "So we know AI can read a contract quickly, but speed is not the same as understanding. There are several things AI consistently misses. It struggles with vague or informal language that implies an obligation without stating it directly. It has no real grasp of how a particular industry actually operates in practice, so unwritten customs and norms go unnoticed. It cannot always account for the legal differences between jurisdictions. It will not pick up on a power imbalance between the two parties, even when that imbalance shifts who bears the real risk. It can miss references to side agreements or verbal commitments that are not written into the contract itself. And perhaps most importantly, it cannot read tone. A clause might be technically neutral on the page but signal bad faith to an experienced human reader. These are not edge cases. They are exactly the kinds of issues that cause problems down the line, and they require human judgement to catch."
        },
        {
          "number": 5,
          "script": "Now, one of the trickiest areas for AI in contract review is something you might not even notice at first glance: the meaning that lives between the lines. Many contracts rely on what lawyers call implied terms, which are obligations that courts will automatically read into an agreement even if they are never actually written down. AI tools are very good at scanning for explicit wording, but they often miss these invisible layers entirely. Then there are phrases like \"reasonable efforts\" or \"in a timely manner,\" which sound straightforward but can mean very different things depending on the industry, the jurisdiction, or the commercial context surrounding the deal. A clause that looks completely standard in one setting might carry quite specific and significant meaning in another. This is where experienced human reviewers really earn their place. They bring judgement and context that no AI tool currently has, spotting where vague or familiar language could quietly create a serious and unexpected liability."
        },
        {
          "number": 6,
          "script": "Now, one of the biggest limitations of AI in contract review is its struggle with context. You see, a contract doesn't exist in a vacuum. It sits within an industry, a relationship, and a legal environment, and AI often misses that bigger picture entirely. For example, certain industries have their own specialised terminology that carries very specific meaning, and AI can misinterpret or simply overlook it. Similarly, if two parties have been negotiating back and forth for weeks, that history shapes how certain clauses should be read, but AI has no access to those conversations. Then there are local legal customs and unwritten business norms, the kind of thing that experienced lawyers just know, that AI simply cannot pick up on. And when language is deliberately vague or ambiguous, AI tends to apply a literal reading rather than understanding the intended meaning. So while AI is fast and thorough in many ways, context is where it genuinely struggles."
        },
        {
          "number": 7,
          "script": "So, where does all of this leave us? The honest answer is that AI can be genuinely useful in contract review, but only when you treat it as a starting point rather than the final word. It is quite good at spotting common clauses and flagging obvious issues, but it can easily miss risks that are specific to your situation or industry. That is why it is so important to always have a qualified legal professional review whatever the AI produces. Think of the AI output as a rough first draft that still needs expert eyes on it. If the AI does highlight something that looks concerning, make a note of it and make sure a human follows up on it properly. And for anything high-value or particularly complex, please do not rely on AI alone. Used wisely, AI saves you time and helps you ask better questions. But the judgement, ultimately, has to come from a person."
        },
        {
          "number": 8,
          "script": "So let us bring everything together. The core message from this lesson is that AI is genuinely useful in contract review, but it has real blind spots. Vague wording, implied obligations, unusual clause combinations, things like unbalanced liability caps or poorly worded termination rights, these are the kinds of issues that often slip past an AI tool entirely. Context matters enormously, and that is something a machine simply cannot replicate. So please do use AI as a helpful first pass, but always bring in a qualified lawyer when the stakes are high or the language is unclear. The final call should always rest with a human. And here is something practical you can do right now: take a contract you are already familiar with, run it through an AI tool, and pay close attention to what it flags and, just as importantly, what it does not. That gap is where your judgement becomes essential."
        }
      ]
    }
